705275f-c.title: Brooklyn: Kings Highway - Farragut Road
705275f-c.text:
King's Highway, at the S.W. corner of Farragut Road, showing the Johannes Ditmars farmhouse. Van Wyck in his book titled Keskachauge states - - - - - "stands probably near site of Jan Stevense (Voorhees) house - - - - -- mentioned in 1695-1696". The Ditmars were lineal
descendants of Jan Stevense (Voorhees).
March 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
The same, as seen from Foster ave.
March 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
The same, another view. Beyond the house is the embankment upon which runs a branch of the Long Island R.R., formerly the N.Y. Brooklyn
and Manhattan Beach R.R.
March 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

705276f-c.title: Brooklyn: Kings Highway - Farragut Road
705276f-c.text:
(1)
King's Highway, at the S.W. corner of Farragut Road; showing the Johannes Ditmars farmhouse. Authorities state that this house was erected in 1736; others 1750, by a Jan Ditmars. Some of the occupants were: Mrs. Ditmars, 1857; Mrs. Johnson, 1860; Cornelius Ditmars, 1903;
and Kirleaney, 1923. It was taken down in 1925.
August 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
The same, as viewed southward.
August 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(3)
The same as No. 2.
August 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(4)
A view of the opposits side, which faces Folger Place.
August 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
